A flag variable is useful because it helps a program keep track of whether something has happened or not. It usually stores a value of True or False and can be used to make decisions in a program. For example, in everyday life, a flag is like checking whether you have finished your homework. If your homework is done, the flag is set to True; if not, it stays False. This makes it easy to know what action to take next, such as relaxing after finishing your work or continuing to study until it is complete.
